You think back to Ray, and the good old days. The stories, the glory and honor of that life. What this man offers is a pale shadow of what you once were.\n\n"Well, what do you say?"\n\nYou fix him with a steely gaze. “You’re no daimyo, and a samurai’s honor is worth more than you can pay. Get out of here.”\n\nThe man inclines his head slightly and turns away. "If you ever change your mind, you can find us here." He drops a small business card on the ground and walks away.\n\nYou know what it is. The location of the local yakuza chapter. Maybe you'll round up some of the old crew and pay them a visit...\n\nTHE END
“Ha! That was great, but nothing compared to when we fought at Totomi. But then, Kaz always tells that one better than I do...”\n\nYou and Ray joke and swap stories at the bar for hours. You could get used to this, you think. It’s not exactly the high adventure life you once led, but it’s nice to enjoy good company and good beer.\n\nOne more thing occurs to you. “Hey Ray. Where is Kaz anyway; you see much of him lately?”\n\n“Yeah, sometimes. Check the temple, he doesn’t get out much.”\n\nYou say goodbye to Ray, and leave the bar a tipsy and in high spirits.\n<<set $befriended_ray = true >>\n<<display Ray Next>>
<<display The Mayors Office>>\n\n<<set $visited_mayor = true >>\n[[Back|Wandering the Streets]]
Rays sadness hangs in the air for several moments. You begin to have second thoughts about coming here. What happened to the happy-go-lucky young samurai you once knew? \nRay abruptly bolts upright, a wry smile spreading across his face.\n\n“Hey Yuu. Remember that time in Mikawa, we crashed the daimyo’s palace? The look on his face when he realized we weren’t statues!”\n\n[[Yeah, I remember|Visiting Ray 5a]]\n[[That's in the past now, Ray|Visiting Ray 5b]]\n
“You’re a smart guy, Ray. Too smart for this. Don’t you think it’s time to start thinking about your future instead of your past.”\n\nRay furrows his brow, irritated. “What future? What else do you think there is to do, huh? Hell, even Kaz spends most of his time sitting on his ass these days. Go see for yourself.”\n\n“I think I might. It would be a nice change to see what a REAL samurai does with his time.” You say, standing up.\n\n“You’ll see it soon, Yuu. You had a great run, but four extra years of work, and you still end up back in Kamakura, same as the rest of us.”\n\nWhat a disappointment. A young man with such potential wasting his life like that. You sigh as you exit the bar. “Good luck, Reijiro,” you whisper.\n\n<<display Ray Next>>

You think back to Kaz and the things he said about desire, and ignorance, and knowing what it is you're fighting for.\n\n“Well, what do you say?”\n\n“That’s a job that’ll never end, for a purpose that’ll never be satisfied. I’ll pass.”\n\n"Very well, Mishima Yuu. If you ever change your mind..."\n\nHe hands you a small business card with the location of a local bar on it, and a password written in tight letters right below it.\n\nYou spend the rest of your days helping out around town. Lending your strength to those less fortunate than yourself.\n\nYou become a good friend to Jufuku-ji and the monks who live there.\n\nIt is a good life.\n\nTHE END
The train’s wheels clack and screech, driving you onward. One step closer to home.
You head off with Mr. Interested Party, who leads you to the local hangout of the Yakuza.\n\nOver the next few years, you slowly sell your soul for money and power. It feels kind of good.\n\nThis is what you were made for.\n\nThis is where you were always heading.\n\nTHE END
It’s late afternoon, but still too early for most people to be getting dinner. As you enter the shop it’s mostly empty, just Nori and her apprentices preparing for that day’s service.\n\nShe’s showing a young man and a young woman how to massage takoyaki. She kneads the octopus expertly, her sleeves rolled up her arms.

You make your way to Jufuku-ji, the Zen temple where you have heard Kaz now spends his days. As you make your way up the road, you try to imagine the big, tough man living life as a gentle monk.\n\nYou make your way through the big red gate that marks the entrance to the temple and follow the path down to the main hall.

[img[raypast]]\n\nRay was young, the youngest of us, in fact. He had this zest for life you don't see much in most samurai. Comes with the territory I guess. It's hard to get excited about your day when you know you're going to be killing (and maybe being killed by) honorable men.\n\nWhat got Ray excited was the other stuff. The little challenges that would come up in the course of a mission. He could pick locks, scale walls, whip up explosives out of nothing... he always had some way in. Some way around the inevitable.\n\nHe had so much potential. We always said he'd be leading his own squad one day. Maybe an army.\n\nHe wanted to come with me, when I said I was going to go work for Big Tex. But the contract was for one. No way around it. Money was tight back then. Still is, I suppose.\n\n<<set $remembered_ray = true >>\n<<display Train Choices>>\n\n/% Acceptance: %/\n[[He was resourceful, though. [img[daibutsupresent]]\n\nKaz doesn’t seem to hear you at first. He sits perfectly still. You almost think he might be asleep. But a moment later he stands, in one fluid motion. His eyes open, and a huge grin fills his face.\n\nKaz: “Mishima!”\n\nHe rushes over to you, catching you in a huge embrace. His robes hang loosely over his large frame, but you can tell that he is still just as strong as he’d been back in the old days. He pulls back slightly, holding your shoulders and taking a good look at you.\n\nKaz: “It’s been too long, my friend.” He smirks ruefully. “You look so much older than when you left!”\n\nMishima: “You too, Kaz, you old bear! What are you doing in a zen temple? I thought you were going to go be a farmer!”\n\n[[Continue|Visiting Kaz 3]]
[img[sushibarpresent]]\n\nMishima: “Hey Nori!”\n\nShe looks up at you and smiles. She takes her hands out of the bowl and motions for one of her apprentices to take over. She motions for you to come over and starts to carefully wash her hands.\n\nShe speaks softly as you approach. “Mishima Yuu. I was starting to wonder if you’d gotten our letter.” She flicks some water at you. “You could have written back, you know.”\n\n[[Continue|Visiting Nori 3]]\n
[img[noripast]]\n\nNori was our specialist. If we needed to take someone out, we'd cover the entrances and she'd take care of the interior. She was fast on her feet and even faster with a blade.\n\nShe was kind though, despite the nature of our work. It was a ritual, an extension of her self. The preparation, the approach, the pursuit, the kill. She wasn't... happy about it. But it didn't faze her. It was just this part of her life.\n\nI thought she'd stay in the game forever. But when the recruiters came calling, she said she'd seen the writing on the wall. She knew what was coming and it was time to change.\n\n<<set $remembered_nori = true >>\n<<display Train Choices>>\n/% Acceptance: %/\n[[She was brave. It's hard to turn away from something that has become a part of you.|$next_train_scene]]\n/% Denial: %/\n[[She could've been the best in the business. Now she's just some civilian. Her loss, I guess.|$next_train_scene]]\n/% Buddhism: %/\n[[She saw that the world would change around us. I wish I’d paid more attention.|$next_train_scene]]
Mishima: “And what should I do instead, Kaz? What other work is there for a samurai?”\n\n“Maybe you can’t carry a sword around anymore, Yuu. But the world still needs strong people. Haibutsu kishaku has made Kamakura a hard place for the devout. People like you and I, we can stand up for the weak. For the defenseless…”\n\nThe two of you talk long into the night, sipping tea and discussing the finer points of Zen buddhism and the old life. It’s near midnight when you finally leave the temple. It was good to see your old friend. Maybe he has a point.\n<<set $befriended_kaz = true >>\n[[Continue|Ending]]
You make your way to the sushi restaurant where you hear Nori works now. She was always good with knives, so you guess it was an easy transition.\n\nThe shop is small, the first floor of one of the old two story shops. You think it used to be a general store when you were in town last. The wooden steps lead up to an ornately decorated storefront.\n\nNori’s Sushi. How appropriate.

Mishima: “I didn’t come here for a lecture, Kaz. Maybe you’re done with that life, but you don’t get to tell me how to live.”\n\nHe looks down, crestfallen. “I’m sorry to hear it, Yuu…”\n\nHe sighs deeply, and meets your eyes one last time. “I’ve had four long years to think about this, Mishima. If you cannot hear me, I only hope that you find a way to the truth on your own.”\n\n“Don’t die for some daimyo’s coin purse, Mishima.”\n\nYou get up and leave the temple. This was a waste of time.\n\n[[Continue|Ending]]
This room is filled with strange statues. Three of Shakyamuni, the Buddha. One of Kannon, boddhisatva of compassion. And two enormous wooden statues of the Heavenly Kings. They must have been moved from Tsurugaoka Hachiman-gū around the time that you left.\n\nYou find Kaz in the center of the room in zazen, seated meditation.
The path to Kamakura is different than you remember it. Fewer samurai and gamblers headed into town to make their luck, and more merchants and aristocrats headed into town to take someone else’s. You wind your way through, making quick time to the city.\n\nKamakura looks different today. The buildings seem taller, the streets seem wider. You feel like a [[stranger|Wandering the Streets]] here.
[img[kazpast]]\n\nKaz. My best friend, Kaz. He could be a scary guy sometimes. Rough, tattooed, and strong as a bear. He was always the one to kick doors down, to get answers in an interrogation. I never thought I'd see him back down from the life.\n\nBut the last job we did together... I guess something changed. He just didn't want to do it anymore. He talked about going out to the country, becoming a farmer.\n\nWe grew up together. Our parents were old friends, and many a day we spent wandering the streets of Kamakura. As I got older, I wanted to leave, to see the world. Kamakura wasn't enough for me. I had to see it all.\n\nBut Kaz, he loved it. He was born there, and he always said that's where he'd die.\n\nKaz, in the fields? I can't see it.\n\n<<set $remembered_kaz = true >>\n<<display Train Choices>>\n\n/% Acceptance: %/\n[[Maybe he wasn’t cut out for this life. The two of you head out to the street and start to make your way toward the Kurumigawa.\n\nMishima: “So! A sushi master. He laughs a bit, clearly amused by this. “AH yes, I remember that conversation…” He leads you over to a few cushions at the side of the room, and the two of you take a seat.\n\n“I couldn’t bring myself to leave Kamakura. But I couldn’t keep going the way I was, either. I needed time to think.” He absent-mindedly smooths the fabric of his robe, carefully considering his next words. “And since you’ve been gone, I’ve had a lot of it.”\n\nMishima: “Oh?”\n\nHe looks up, meets your eyes, suddenly looking quite serious. “Do you know the Second Noble Truth, Mishima?”\n\nMishima: “Sorry Kaz, can’t say I do...”\n\nHis eyes scan your own, pity betraying itself in the corners of his face. He takes a slow, deep breath before speaking again. “Well, Shakyamuni teaches us that the root of all suffering can be traced back to two things. Desire, and ignorance.”\n\nHe waits for you to nod, to signal some kind of understanding.\n\nMishima: “Okay?”\n\n[[Continue|Visiting Kaz 4]]
You think back to Nori and the things she said about accepting change and learning to live in a new way.\n\n"Well, what do you say?"\n\n“Sorry, pal. I think... I think I’m not a samurai anymore. I think it’s time for a change.”\n\nYou turn and walk away from Mr. Interested Party, winding your back up the path toward Nori's sushi shop.\n\nYou don't know what you'll do for a living. But there's plenty of time to figure it out. And your friends are here to help.\n\nTHE END
[img[kamakurapast]]\n\nThe Kamakura I remember was a bustling town. Shops everywhere, no buildings much higher than two stories.\n\nSince shinbutsu bunri, the buddhist temples were being dismantled and destroyed, but Kamakura still had the big bronze statue of the Great Buddha, and the Tsurugaoka Hachimangū, the Shinto shrine that marks the center of the city.\n\nThere were bars and brothels. Gamblers, mercenaries, people out to make their fortune.\n\nAnd there was always something going on. Always some intrigue among those in charge, being played out in the streets and alleys of the city.\n\nKamakura was once a bastion of military might, the seat of the Kamakura shogunate six centuries ago. And rightly so. It's a natural fortress. The only way in or out of town is by sea, or through one of the Seven Entrances, narrow artificial passes cut into the hills.\n\nThe Kurumi river crosses through, winding its way down to the beach, changing names as it goes: Nameri, Zazen, Ebisudō, Sumiuri, Enmadō. A different name for each stage of its life...\n\nThe city’s name doesn’t change. But its people might.\n\n<<set $remembered_kamakura = true >>\n<<display Train Choices>>\n[[It’s been four years since I was there last.|$next_train_scene]]

“The kind you’re good at, Mishima. We’ve got some problems that a samurai would be good for solving.”\n\n[[“I see.”|Ending4]]
“An interested party. We heard you were back in town. Might have a job for you.”\n\n[[“What kind of job?”|Ending3]]
You inch forward in your seat as you feel the train’s momentum begin to shift.. The clacking of the wheels comes farther and farther apart now, and the trees and hills outside your window pass slower and slower.\n\nYou hear the steam whistle blow. You have arrived at [[Ofuna station|Train Facts]], 6 kilometers outside Kamakura.
Mishima: “I wasn’t sure what to say! ‘Kamakura is different, Mishima.’ ‘Yes, well, Tosa is exactly the same,’ isn’t the most interesting letter to send.”\n\nShe dries her hands on an old towel, white, embroidered with little green frogs. “We were worried about you.”\n\nMishima: “Yes, well…”\nYou pause for a moment. She’s not looking for an excuse.\n\n“I’m not looking for an excuse, Yuu. I’m just letting you know.” Her tone is sweet, not judgemental, not upset. She’s genuinely happy to see you.\n\nMishima: “The letter was good, really. I needed it. Something to come to back to.”\n\nShe makes her way around the counter. “Let’s go for a walk.”\n\nShe catches your quizzical look. “My apprentices can handle the shop until I get back. They’re good kids.”\n\n[[Continue|Visiting Nori 4]]
You're in the Sheriff's Office.

“The work we used to do… the daimyo… fighting over land, over wealth...” He stops, trying to conjure the right words to make you understand.\n\n“Desires like that can never be satisfied, Mishima. People will fight, and die, forever. For something they can never truly attain. It’s not worth it.”\n\n[[Maybe he's right|Visiting Kaz 4a]]\n[[No, some things need to be fought for|Visiting Kaz 4b]]

Is this the main street?\n\nYou see no samurai like yourself. Merchants are milling about, hawking their wares to the few customers who are dotting the streets. You pass a group of women shuffling along in frilly dresses and boots. They stop to gawk at you; with your swords and traditional dress, you stand out. “Are you lost?” one of the women asks.\n\nYou don’t know what to say.\n\n“If you’re hungry, traveler, there’s a [[good sushi place|Visiting Nori]] down the way. Oh, and if you’re thirsty, take a left, you’ll find [[the bar|Visiting Ray]].”
<<display The Empty Saloon>>\n\n<<set $visited_saloon = true >>\n[[Back|Wandering the Streets]]
It’s late at night now. Back in town for a day and already you’re wondering if you should even have come back at all.\n\nYou find yourself walking in Shakado Pass, one of the many narrow roads that was cut into the hills surrounding and throughout Kamakura. This one cuts through the hills between the \n\nShakado Pass was once home to another buddhist temple, built by the third regent of the Kamakura shogunate. It was closed and its artifacts removed a long time ago, but the name remains.\n\n<<if $befriended_kaz>>\nIt was good to see Kaz. He always seemed so strong. I had no idea how much the life had cost him. But the temple, Shakyamuni’s teachings, they seem to have given him purpose. A way to recover from the bloodshed that dominated our lives for so long.\n<<else>>\nI can’t believe what’s become of Kaz. He always seemed so strong. But one bad day in the field and he retreats to a life of solitude and inaction… Was he really that fragile?\n<<endif>>\n<<if $befriended_nori>>\nNori’s doing well for herself. She has pride and skill at her new profession, and it suits her. I suppose that leaving the life behind doesn’t have to be the end. There are still battles to win, even if they can’t be won with a sword.\n<<else>>\nNori… how could she change so much in so little time? When I knew her she was smart, capable, and deadlier than most. But now what? She only wants to chop sushi?\n\nShe could have been so much more.\n<<endif>>\n<<if $befriended_ray>>\nIt was good to see Ray. He could have had a real career as a storyteller. Still might. We could spend plenty of nights whiling away at the tavern, telling tales of the old days. It’ll be good to have a friend like that here. Someone else to remember what it was like.\n<<else>>\nRay. Reduced to a drunken mess of a man. He always had such a bright future, but now... What led to this? Is it because he quit the life, or because he couldn’t let it go?\n<<endif>>\n\nYou find yourself standing before the yagura tombs. Holes cut in the sides of the hills as grave sites for important nobles and military leaders.\n\nYou hear a noise off to the left. You turn to see an unfamiliar face. A man dressed all in black. He has a curved, pointed nose, and scars in several places. He looks like a gangster.\n\n“Mishima Yuu?”\n\n[[“Who’s asking?”|Ending2]]

[img[letter]]\n\nYou hold a crinkled letter. The paper is yellowed, delicate. You got it six months ago, an unexpected treasure from Kamakura.\n\nYour friends there wrote it, a few years after you left for your most recent job. They hadn’t seen you in years, but they still remembered. Still thought you were worth writing to. Maybe they saw you as a tie back to the life they had each left behind, for one reason or another. Maybe they were worried you had died.\n\nEither way, the letter had been a lifeline. When the job ended, you had somewhere to go. People to see one more time.\n\n“To Mishima Yuu,\nFrom [[Enya Kazuya|Remembering Kaz]], [[Yamagata Noriko|Remembering Nori]], and [[Takemi Reijiro|Remembering Ray]]”\n\nYou’ve read it a hundred times. Life’s different in [[Kamakura|Remembering Kamakura]] now, they say.
<<display The Letter>>\n\n<<display The Train>>
Mishima: “What do you think I should do?”\n\nYou turn and meet her eyes. She looks so much older, so much wiser than she was four years ago. Something in you knows she’s right. Times are changing, and it’s going to be a lot harder to change with them when everyone else has the same realization.\n\n“Find a job here in town, Yuu. Something simple, something pure that you can master. Work at it every day. Pour your heart and soul into it. That’s how you change. You find something worthy, and you let it take the reins.”\n\nThe two of you sit at the bench for a while, watching the fish jump, and sun start to set. Eventually you walk with Nori back to the sushi shop. You have some fresh tuna and set out for one more visit.\n<<set $befriended_nori = true >>\n<<display Nori Next>>
You're in the saloon. It's pretty empty right now.
Matt Kaemmerer, CJ Hostetter, Willow Vaughan
Mishima: “That day won’t come for a long time, Nori. I’m not going to give up everything I am just because some Emperor raises the taxes.”\n\nYou shrug her hand off of your shoulder.\n\nA touch of anger in her eyes. You’ve struck a chord. “Change is inevitable, Yuu. Don’t blame me if you can’t take it.”\n\nThe two of you sit in stony silence for a while. Eventually Nori gets up to leave, heading back to her sushi shop.\n\n<<display Nori Next>>
She absent-mindedly kicks a stone out of the path. “The time for violence is coming to an end. All the battles have been won. It’s time to build something new in the wreckage.”\n\nShe kneels down to pick a flower growing between the stones in the path. She hands it to you. “It’s time to stop fighting.”\n\nThe two of you walk for while, eventually coming to a wooden bench on the bank of the river. You remember this spot. You, Ray, Kaz, and Nori used to come here now and then. You look out over the rushing waters.\n\nNori puts a hand on your shoulder. “Yuu. Even Samurai get old eventually. What are you going to do when it happens to you?”\n\n\n[[I've been thinking about it...|Visiting Nori 6a]]\n\n[[Get old? I'm in this until the end|Visiting Nori 6b]]
As your eyes adjust to the dim room, you spot a familiar looking figure hunched over the bar. Could it be?
